{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a59cbdba-b2c0-45b7-bc08-642438565725","content":"No files found in the working directory, so I'll walk you through the conversion directly.\n\n## Converting to Compiled Bindings\n\n**1. Add `x:DataType` to your ContentPage root element:**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             xmlns:vm=\"clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels\"\n             x:Class=\"YourApp.Views.SettingsPage\"\n             x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\">\n\n    <VerticalStackLayout>\n        <Label Text=\"{Binding Theme}\" />\n        <Switch IsToggled=\"{Binding NotificationsEnabled}\" />\n        <Label Text=\"{Binding FontSize, StringFormat='Font Size: {0}'}\" />\n    </VerticalStackLayout>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe only changes needed are:\n- Add the `xmlns:vm` namespace pointing to your ViewModel's CLR namespace.\n- Add `x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\"` to the `<ContentPage>`.\n\nYour existing `{Binding …}` expressions stay the same — the XAML compiler now resolves them against `SettingsViewModel` at build time.\n\n## Catching Binding Errors at Build Time\n\n**2. Enable strict mode in your `.csproj`:**\n\n```xml\n<!-- In your .csproj <PropertyGroup> -->\n<StrictXamlCompilation>true</StrictXamlCompilation>\n```\n\nWith this flag **and** `x:DataType` in place:\n\n| Error type | Caught at build? |\n|---|---|\n| Misspelled property (`Theeme`) | ✅ Yes |\n| Wrong type in converter | ✅ Yes |\n| Missing property on VM | ✅ Yes |\n| Missing `x:DataType` (untyped binding) | ⚠️ Warning → error with strict mode |\n\n**3. Opting out selectively** — if a subtree must use runtime binding (e.g., for a `DataTemplateSelector`), set `x:DataType=\"\"` on that element to disable compiled bindings locally.\n\n**Key points:**\n- `x:DataType` turns `{Binding}` into a compiled binding automatically — no syntax change needed.\n- Strict XAML compilation promotes untyped-binding warnings to errors, so nothing slips through.\n- The BindingContext assignment in code-behind stays unchanged.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b3c39e38-a601-4289-9d63-dcc10ecb086d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. The user is asking me to help them convert a hypothetical SettingsPage.xaml to use compiled bindings. Since there are no files, I'll provide guidance and examples directly.","outputTokens":659,"requestId":"77C2:176D78:7EDDAE6:8D07C69:69EABD84"},"id":"cb4c2977-14bb-4fae-af8f-9058e1c2e65c","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:47:14.614Z","parentId":"f36c24dc-fdd7-4970-8d69-c8ef0bdc52fb"}
